SIMPLE: clink
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clink
<hw>Clink</hw> <pr>(kl⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Clinked</conjf>
<pr>(kl⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Clinking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>clinken</ets>; akin to
G. <ets>klingen</ets>, D. <ets>klinken</ets>, SW. <ets>klinga</ets>,
Dan. <ets>klinge</ets>; prob. of imitative origin. Cf. <er>Clank</er>,
<er>Clench</er>, <er>Click</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To cause
to give out a slight, sharp, tinkling, sound, as by striking metallic or
other sonorous bodies together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And let me the canakin <qex>clink</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Clink
<hw>Clink</hw> <pr>(kl⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To give out a slight, sharp, tinkling sound.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>clinking</xex> latch.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rhyme. <mark>[Humorous]</mark>.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Clink
<hw>Clink</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A slight, sharp, tinkling sound, made
by the collision of sonorous bodies.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>Clink</qex> and
fall of swords.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Clink
<hw>Clink</hw> <pr>(kl⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A prison
cell; a lockup; -- probably orig. the name of the noted prison in
Southwark, England.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧I'm here in the
<xex>clink</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Kipling.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clinkant</ent>⟦br⟧
